==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang}} ''[[bindan]]'', from {{proto|Germanic|benđanan}} (compare West Frisian {{term|bine|lang=fy}}, Dutch/German ''[[binden]]''), from {{proto|Indo-European|bhendh-}} 'to tie' (compare Welsh {{term|benn|lang=cy}} 'cart', Latin {{term|offendix|offendīx|lang=la}} 'knot, band', Lithuanian {{term|beñdras|lang=lt}} 'partner', Ancient Greek {{term|peîsma}} 'cable, rope', Sanskrit {{term|badhnāti}} 'he binds').

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/baɪnd/}}
* {{audio|en-us-bind.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|aɪnd}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# That which binds or ties.
# A [[troublesome]] situation; a [[problem]]; a [[predicament]] or [[quandary]].
# Any twining or climbing plant or stem, especially a [[hop]] vine; a [[bine]].
# {{music}} A [[ligature]] or [[tie]] for grouping notes.

====Synonyms====
* See also [[Wikisaurus:difficult situation]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|binds|binding|bound|'''[[bound]]''' ''or rarely'' '''[[bounden]]'''}}

# To [[connect]]
# To [[couple]]
# To put together in a cover, as of books
# {{computing}} to associate an [[identifier]] with a value; to associate a variable name with the content of a storage location

